<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos montereyensis </i>is a long-lived manzanita that lacks a lignotuber and is an obligate seeder. Seeds germinate after fire from heat scarification, and seedling establishment is abundant after fires. Shrubs gain dominance with time and create a closed shrub canopy that adds to the seed bank. Stands require periodic fire to maintain current species composition. Infrequent fire results in tree encroachment and decline in shrub vigor and seed bank quality, while frequent fire tends to convert stands to coastal scrub or grassland. Greenlee and Langenheim (1990) and Van Dyke et al. (2001) consider the historic fire cycle to be between 10 and 100 years, though fire return intervals are likely > 30 years to maintain stands. <br/>
<br/>
Stands dominated by <i>Arcostaphylos montereyensis </i>(a CNPS list 1B plant) contain several other rare and federally listed taxa. <i>A. hookeri </i>ssp. <i>hookeri, A. pajaroensis, Ericameria fasciculata, </i>and <i>Piperia yadonii </i>are CNPS list 1B plants; <i>Ceanothus cuneatus </i>var. <i>rigidus </i>is a CNPS list 4 plant. <i>Chorizanthe pungens </i>var. <i>pungens </i>is federally listed as threatened, and <i>P. yadonii </i>is listed as endangered. This alliance is a component of the maritime chaparral (see maritime chaparral discussion in the Changes Since the First Edition section). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands occur in the Central California Coast (261B) on Bureau of Land Management lands at Fort Ord Military Reservation, at Jacks Peak and Toro county parks, and at nearby areas. Further study will determine the differences between this and other maritime chaparral alliances, especially the <i>Arctostaphylos</i> (<i>crustacea, tomentosa</i>) alliance. </div>
</div>

	

    
